n strain.\n- Nonlinear softening/yielding behavior → captured by quadratic terms.\n- Temperature effects reducing stress → captured by linear/quadratic temperature terms.\n- Interaction between strain and temperature → captured by the cross-term.\n\nYou can extend this further by adding cubic or other nonlinear terms if needed. But this provides a solid base reflecting the physical insights from your data analysis.', 'Based on the analysis and ideas, a good mathematical function skeleton for stress (y) as a function of strain (x0) and temperature (x1) should:\n\n- Include linear terms in x0 and x1 to capture first-order effects.\n- Include quadratic terms in x0² and x1² to capture nonlinearities observed in mid and high ranges.\n- Include an interaction term x0*x1 to capture coupling effects between strain and temperature.\n- Ensure params has at least 12 elements to avoid index errors.\n\nThis leads to a polynomial regression-like skeleton:\n\n\\[\ny = p_0 + p_1 x_0 + p_2 x_1 + p_3 x_0^2 + p_4 x_1^2 + p_5 (x_0 \\times x_1) + \\text{(optional higher order or interaction terms)}\n\\]\n\nTo fill up 12 parameters, we can add cubic or cross terms like \\(x_0^3\\), \\(x_1^3\\), \\(x_0^2 x_1\\), \\(x_0 x_1^2\\), etc., but for the skeleton, quadratic plus interaction terms are usually sufficient.\n\n---\n\n### Here is the implementation of `equation_v1` with these considerations:\n\n```python\ndef equation_v1(x0: np.ndarray, x1: np.ndarray, params: np.ndarray) -> np.ndarray:\n    """Improved version of `equation_v0`.\n\n    Includes linear, quadratic, and interaction terms of strain (x0) and temperature (x1).\n\n    Parameters:\n    - params (np.ndarray): Trainable coefficients with length >= 12.\n\n    Returns:\n    - y (np.ndarray): Predicted stress values.\n    """\n    # Validate params length\n    if len(params) < MAX_NPARAMS:\n        raise ValueError(f"params must have at least {MAX_NPARAMS} elements")\n\n    # Compute polynomial terms\n    y = (\n        params[0] 